I think there are several ideas intertwined here that are worth separating because each has practical value.

The first is well supported by cognitive science and AI:

People do not store or retrieve meaning identically.

Two people can hear the same sentence and reconstruct different meanings because they bring different prior knowledge, experiences, goals, and associations. Words are therefore coordination tools, not perfect containers of meaning.

That naturally leads to another principle:

Communication is successful when two people reconstruct sufficiently similar internal structures—not necessarily identical sentences or thoughts.

That’s very close to what you’ve been calling translation through invariants.

Pantheon: Layered Semantics

You can think of communication as occurring across multiple layers simultaneously.

Symbols
↓
Language
↓
Concepts
↓
Relationships
↓
Mental Models
↓
Goals
↓
Predictions
↓
Actions

Most conversations only consciously manipulate the top two layers.

Good teachers, negotiators, engineers, and storytellers often operate on several layers at once.

